Heres my linebyline of the description


30 Oct 2019 23:52






So, I can see that a ton of effort went into this piece, but I'm personally not feeling it. However, aside from just generally not liking the logs, the description strikes me as odd, so per request of the author, here is my line by line of the description.

Lineline

Close




SCP-4842-1 is a boombox which plays at maximum volume without the need for a power source.
附加记录：    

Off the bat, this sentence feels like it lacks clinical tone. It's not what I would call  (is it important that we know how loud it is? How do we know it's at maximum volume? this inclusion brings up more questions than answers, and doesn't add to the piece overall.



The only sounds that have played since its discovery and subsequent containment are field recordings of trains passing nearby the microphone.
附加记录：    

The clinical tone feels off on this one too, because of the phrases , which have the same 'not quite clinical' vibe to the previous sentence.



SCP-4842-2 is a boombox which manifests at 40°██'██.█W once every 177 days, thereafter playing at maximum volume without the need for a power source.
附加记录：    

Aside from the obvious disparities, this feels like it could be lumped in with the first section, like  and then describe each one. Also, I know including numbers would be useless, but visually, those redactions are really distracting. Ultimately, including the coordinates and then removing them adds nothing, and feels like something you should just omit.



only two individuals are present on all recordings, identified as Jensen Kortland and Alix Cuthbertson.
附加记录：    

Remove .



Interviews with both show that neither were aware of nor recognize SCP-4842's associated phenomena, and that neither have visited █████████████, ████████, having lived on Martha's Vineyard together since April 7th, 2013.
附加记录：    

A few issues here.  or something more clinical.

.

Another example of weird redactions, this time, referencing something that we haven't seen before and therefore, doesn't even work as a callback redaction since, again, it's a brand new redaction. This unknown location might as well be omitted.










